description: ZrSe₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ZrSe₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Zr(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 8-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Se(1,2)¹⁻ and four equivalent Se(3)¹⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (2.765 Å) and two longer (2.766 Å) Zr(1)-Se(1,2) bond lengths. There are two shorter (2.749 Å) and two longer (2.902 Å) Zr(1)-Se(3) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent Se¹⁻ sites. In the first Se¹⁻ site, Se(1,2)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Zr(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second Se¹⁻ site, Se(3)¹⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Zr(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing SeZr₄ trigonal pyramids.

BiTeCl is Molybdenite-derived structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one BiTeCl sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ and three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form distorted edge-sharing BiTe₃Cl₃ octahedra. All Bi(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 3.050 Å. All Bi(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.958 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms.

AlSiTe₃ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅31m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one AlSiTe₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Al(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Te(1)¹⁻ atoms to form AlTe₆ octahedra that share corners with six equivalent Si(1)SiTe₃ tetrahedra and edges with three equivalent Al(1)Te₆ octahedra. All Al(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.859 Å. Si(1) is bonded to one Si(1) and three equivalent Te(1)¹⁻ atoms to form SiSiTe₃ tetrahedra that share corners with six equivalent Al(1)Te₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 80°. The Si(1)-Si(1) bond length is 2.309 Å. All Si(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.543 Å. Te(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to two equivalent Al(1)³⁺ and one Si(1) atom.

ZnCl₂ crystallizes in the tetragonal P̅4m2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ZnCl₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Zn(1)²⁺ is bonded to four equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form corner-sharing ZnCl₄ tetrahedra. All Zn(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.299 Å. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent Zn(1)²⁺ atoms.

AlTeI₇ crystallizes in the triclinic P1 space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of one AlTeI₇ ribbon oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. Al(1)³⁺ is bonded to one I(1)¹⁻, one I(2)¹⁻, one I(3)¹⁻, and one I(4)¹⁻ atom to form AlI₄ tetrahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Te(1)I₆ octahedra and  an edgeedge with one Te(1)I₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 63°. The Al(1)-I(1) bond length is 2.502 Å. The Al(1)-I(2) bond length is 2.583 Å. The Al(1)-I(3) bond length is 2.594 Å. The Al(1)-I(4) bond length is 2.604 Å. Te(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to one I(2)¹⁻, one I(3)¹⁻, one I(4)¹⁻, one I(5)¹⁻, one I(6)¹⁻, and one I(7)¹⁻ atom to form distorted TeI₆ octahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Al(1)I₄ tetrahedra and  an edgeedge with one Al(1)I₄ tetrahedra. The Te(1)-I(2) bond length is 3.336 Å. The Te(1)-I(3) bond length is 3.276 Å. The Te(1)-I(4) bond length is 3.335 Å. The Te(1)-I(5) bond length is 2.779 Å. The Te(1)-I(6) bond length is 2.795 Å. The Te(1)-I(7) bond length is 2.796 Å. There are seven inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ atom. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted bent 120 degrees geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the third I¹⁻ site, I(3)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the fourth I¹⁻ site, I(4)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the fifth I¹⁻ site, I(5)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the sixth I¹⁻ site, I(6)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the seventh I¹⁻ site, I(7)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Te(1)⁴⁺ atom.

InSe is black P-derived structured and crystallizes in the triclinic P̅1 space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of one InSe ribbon oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. In(1)²⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (2.677 Å) and one longer (2.732 Å) In(1)-Se(1) bond length. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent In(1)²⁺ atoms.

SrBiO₂Br is Bixbyite (Mn,Fe)2O4-derived structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmma space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one SrBiO₂Br sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sr(1)²⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Sr(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.492 Å. Both Sr(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 3.246 Å. Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Bi(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.234 Å. Both Bi(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 3.473 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to two equivalent Sr(1)²⁺, two equivalent Bi(1)³⁺, and two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge, corner, and face-sharing OSr₂Bi₂Br₂ tetrahedra. Both O(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 3.571 Å. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 8-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Sr(1)²⁺, two equivalent Bi(1)³⁺, and four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms.

Na₂Pd₃O₄ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Na₂Pd₃O₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Na(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. All Na(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.293 Å. There are two inequivalent Pd²⁺ sites. In the first Pd²⁺ site, Pd(1)²⁺ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. All Pd(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.055 Å. In the second Pd²⁺ site, Pd(2)²⁺ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. All Pd(2)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.073 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to two equivalent Na(1)¹⁺, one Pd(2)²⁺, and two equivalent Pd(1)²⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge, corner, and face-sharing ONa₂Pd₃ trigonal bipyramids.

KCN crystallizes in the triclinic P1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one KCN sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. K(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to three equivalent N(1)³⁻ atoms. There are a spread of K(1)-N(1) bond distances ranging from 2.776-3.109 Å. C(1)²⁺ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one N(1)³⁻ atom. The C(1)-N(1) bond length is 1.176 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to three equivalent K(1)¹⁺ and one C(1)²⁺ atom.

Te₄O₉ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3 space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of six TeO clusters and two TeO₆ clusters. In each TeO cluster, Te(2)+4.50+ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one O(3)²⁻ atom. The Te(2)-O(3) bond length is 1.919 Å. O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Te(2)+4.50+ atom. In each TeO₆ cluster, Te(1)+4.50+ is bonded in an octahedral geometry to three equivalent O(1)²⁻ and three equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. All Te(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.926 Å. All Te(1)-O(2) bond lengths are 1.989 Å. There are two inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Te(1)+4.50+ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Te(1)+4.50+ atom.

Rb₃Mo₂Cl₉ crystallizes in the hexagonal P̅6m2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Rb₃Mo₂Cl₉ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are two inequivalent Rb¹⁺ sites. In the first Rb¹⁺ site, Rb(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms. All Rb(1)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 3.521 Å. In the second Rb¹⁺ site, Rb(2)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ and six equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms to form RbCl₁₂ cuboctahedra that share corners with six equivalent Rb(2)Cl₁₂ cuboctahedra and faces with six equivalent Mo(1)Cl₆ octahedra. All Rb(2)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 3.447 Å. All Rb(2)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 3.524 Å. Mo(1)³⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ and three equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms to form MoCl₆ octahedra that share faces with three equivalent Rb(2)Cl₁₂ cuboctahedra and  a faceface with one Mo(1)Cl₆ octahedra. All Mo(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.398 Å. All Mo(1)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 2.500 Å. There are two inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one Rb(2)¹⁺ and one Mo(1)³⁺ atom. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Rb(1)¹⁺, two equivalent Rb(2)¹⁺, and two equivalent Mo(1)³⁺ atoms.

NbSe₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one NbSe₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing NbSe₆ octahedra. All Nb(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.624 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

NbOBr₂ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmm2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one NbOBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nb(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent O(1)²⁻, two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻, and two equivalent Br(2)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing NbBr₄O₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 3°. There is one shorter (1.865 Å) and one longer (2.060 Å) Nb(1)-O(1) bond length. Both Nb(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.609 Å. Both Nb(1)-Br(2) bond lengths are 2.695 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms. There are two inequivalent Br¹⁻ sites. In the first Br¹⁻ site, Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the second Br¹⁻ site, Br(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Nb(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

ZrNCl crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ZrNCl sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Zr(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a 7-coordinate geometry to four equivalent N(1)³⁻ and three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. There are three shorter (2.141 Å) and one longer (2.184 Å) Zr(1)-N(1) bond length. All Zr(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.765 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Zr(1)⁴⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing NZr₄ tetrahedra. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Zr(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

Ta₂PdSe₆ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Ta₂PdSe₆ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ta(1)⁵⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Se(1)²⁻, two equivalent Se(2)²⁻, and three equivalent Se(3)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and face-sharing TaSe₇ pentagonal bipyramids. Both Ta(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.623 Å. Both Ta(1)-Se(2) bond lengths are 2.629 Å. There are two shorter (2.643 Å) and one longer (2.770 Å) Ta(1)-Se(3) bond length. Pd(1)²⁺ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to two equivalent Se(1)²⁻ and two equivalent Se(2)²⁻ atoms. Both Pd(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.480 Å. Both Pd(1)-Se(2) bond lengths are 2.476 Å. There are three inequivalent Se²⁻ sites. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Ta(1)⁵⁺ and one Pd(1)²⁺ atom. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Ta(1)⁵⁺ and one Pd(1)²⁺ atom. In the third Se²⁻ site, Se(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Ta(1)⁵⁺ atoms.

ErAg(PSe₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P312 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ErAg(PSe₃)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Er(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form ErSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ag(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Er(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.844 Å. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms to form AgSe₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Er(1)Se₆ octahedra. All Ag(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.924 Å. P(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. All P(1)-Se(1) bond lengths are 2.215 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Er(1)³⁺, one Ag(1)¹⁺, and one P(1)⁴⁺ atom.

PdSCl crystallizes in the monoclinic Pm space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of one PdSCl ribbon oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are four inequivalent Pd³⁺ sites. In the first Pd³⁺ site, Pd(1)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted rectangular see-saw-like geometry to one S(1)²⁻, one S(3)²⁻, one Cl(1)¹⁻, and one Cl(4)¹⁻ atom. The Pd(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.306 Å. The Pd(1)-S(3) bond length is 2.309 Å. The Pd(1)-Cl(1) bond length is 2.393 Å. The Pd(1)-Cl(4) bond length is 2.407 Å. In the second Pd³⁺ site, Pd(2)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted rectangular see-saw-like geometry to one S(1)²⁻, one S(3)²⁻, one Cl(2)¹⁻, and one Cl(3)¹⁻ atom. The Pd(2)-S(1) bond length is 2.305 Å. The Pd(2)-S(3) bond length is 2.310 Å. The Pd(2)-Cl(2) bond length is 2.395 Å. The Pd(2)-Cl(3) bond length is 2.398 Å. In the third Pd³⁺ site, Pd(3)³⁺ is bonded in a rectangular see-saw-like geometry to two equivalent S(2)²⁻ and two equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms. Both Pd(3)-S(2) bond lengths are 2.311 Å. Both Pd(3)-Cl(2) bond lengths are 2.408 Å. In the fourth Pd³⁺ site, Pd(4)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted trigonal bipyramidal geometry to two equivalent S(2)²⁻, one Cl(3)¹⁻, and two equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms. Both Pd(4)-S(2) bond lengths are 2.309 Å. The Pd(4)-Cl(3) bond length is 3.011 Å. Both Pd(4)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.417 Å. There are three inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one Pd(1)³⁺, one Pd(2)³⁺, and one S(2)²⁻ atom. The S(1)-S(2) bond length is 2.155 Å. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted L-shaped geometry to one Pd(3)³⁺, one Pd(4)³⁺, and one S(1)²⁻ atom. In the third S²⁻ site, S(3)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Pd(1)³⁺, one Pd(2)³⁺, and one S(3)²⁻ atom. The S(3)-S(3) bond length is 2.159 Å. There are four inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to one Pd(1)³⁺ and one Pd(4)³⁺ atom. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to one Pd(2)³⁺ and one Pd(3)³⁺ atom. In the third Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(3)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Pd(4)³⁺ and two equivalent Pd(2)³⁺ atoms. In the fourth Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(4)¹⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Pd(1)³⁺ atoms.

AgNO₂ crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmm2 space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of one AgNO₂ ribbon oriented in the (0, 1, 0) direction. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one N(1)³⁺ and two equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. The Ag(1)-N(1) bond length is 2.133 Å. Both Ag(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.370 Å. N(1)³⁺ is bonded in a trigonal planar geometry to one Ag(1)¹⁺ and two equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. Both N(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.256 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Ag(1)¹⁺ and one N(1)³⁺ atom.

NiO₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one NiO₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ni(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing NiO₆ octahedra. All Ni(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.882 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Ni(1)⁴⁺ atoms.

TmOI crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TmOI sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Tm(1)³⁺ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent O(1)²⁻ and four equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Tm(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 2.212 Å. All Tm(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.329 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to four equivalent Tm(1)³⁺ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing OTm₄ tetrahedra. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Tm(1)³⁺ atoms.

AlSeBr₇ crystallizes in the triclinic P1 space group. The structure is one-dimensional and consists of one AlSeBr₇ ribbon oriented in the (1, 0, 0) direction. Al(1)³⁺ is bonded to one Br(1)+0.14-, one Br(2)+0.14-, one Br(3)+0.14-, and one Br(4)+0.14- atom to form AlBr₄ tetrahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Se(1)Br₆ octahedra and  an edgeedge with one Se(1)Br₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 60°. The Al(1)-Br(1) bond length is 2.259 Å. The Al(1)-Br(2) bond length is 2.342 Å. The Al(1)-Br(3) bond length is 2.354 Å. The Al(1)-Br(4) bond length is 2.367 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded to one Br(2)+0.14-, one Br(3)+0.14-, one Br(4)+0.14-, one Br(5)+0.14-, one Br(6)+0.14-, and one Br(7)+0.14- atom to form distorted SeBr₆ octahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Al(1)Br₄ tetrahedra and  an edgeedge with one Al(1)Br₄ tetrahedra. The Se(1)-Br(2) bond length is 3.012 Å. The Se(1)-Br(3) bond length is 2.959 Å. The Se(1)-Br(4) bond length is 3.038 Å. The Se(1)-Br(5) bond length is 2.382 Å. The Se(1)-Br(6) bond length is 2.405 Å. The Se(1)-Br(7) bond length is 2.401 Å. There are seven inequivalent Br+0.14- sites. In the first Br+0.14- site, Br(1)+0.14- is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ atom. In the second Br+0.14- site, Br(2)+0.14- is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Se(1)²⁻ atom. In the third Br+0.14- site, Br(3)+0.14- is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Se(1)²⁻ atom. In the fourth Br+0.14- site, Br(4)+0.14- is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Al(1)³⁺ and one Se(1)²⁻ atom. In the fifth Br+0.14- site, Br(5)+0.14- is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ atom. In the sixth Br+0.14- site, Br(6)+0.14- is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ atom. In the seventh Br+0.14- site, Br(7)+0.14- is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ atom.

SnSe is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two SnSe clusters. Sn(1)²⁺ is bonded in a distorted single-bond geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ atom. The Sn(1)-Se(1) bond length is 2.719 Å. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Sn(1)²⁺ atom.

CaPbI₄ crystallizes in the triclinic P̅1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CaPbI₄ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ca(1)²⁺ is bonded to two equivalent I(1)¹⁻ and four equivalent I(2)¹⁻ atoms to form CaI₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Ca(1)I₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Pb(1)I₆ octahedra. Both Ca(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.141 Å. All Ca(1)-I(2) bond lengths are 3.142 Å. Pb(1)²⁺ is bonded to two equivalent I(2)¹⁻ and four equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms to form PbI₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Pb(1)I₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Ca(1)I₆ octahedra. Both Pb(1)-I(2) bond lengths are 3.243 Å. There are two shorter (3.245 Å) and two longer (3.246 Å) Pb(1)-I(1) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent I¹⁻ sites. In the first I¹⁻ site, I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Ca(1)²⁺ and two equivalent Pb(1)²⁺ atoms. In the second I¹⁻ site, I(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Ca(1)²⁺ and one Pb(1)²⁺ atom.

CdBr₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CdBr₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Cd(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CdBr₆ octahedra. All Cd(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.807 Å. Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Cd(1)²⁺ atoms.

ScAg(PS₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P312 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one ScAg(PS₃)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sc(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form ScS₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Ag(1)S₆ octahedra. All Sc(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.608 Å. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form AgS₆ octahedra that share edges with three equivalent Sc(1)S₆ octahedra. All Ag(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.807 Å. P(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to three equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms. All P(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.042 Å. S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Sc(1)³⁺, one Ag(1)¹⁺, and one P(1)⁴⁺ atom.

NdI₂ crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/mmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one NdI₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Nd(1)²⁺ is bonded in a body-centered cubic geometry to eight equivalent I(1)¹⁻ atoms. All Nd(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 3.325 Å. I(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Nd(1)²⁺ atoms.

TiCl₃ is Bismuth triodide-like structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TiCl₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)³⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ and four equivalent Cl(2)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing TiCl₆ octahedra. Both Ti(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.405 Å. There are two shorter (2.411 Å) and two longer (2.452 Å) Ti(1)-Cl(2) bond lengths. There are two inequivalent Cl¹⁻ sites. In the first Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)³⁺ atoms. In the second Cl¹⁻ site, Cl(2)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)³⁺ atoms.

Pd₅AlI₂ crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/mmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Pd₅AlI₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are two inequivalent Pd sites. In the first Pd site, Pd(1) is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Pd(2), two equivalent Al(1), and two equivalent I(1) atoms. Both Pd(1)-Pd(2) bond lengths are 2.696 Å. Both Pd(1)-Al(1) bond lengths are 2.696 Å. Both Pd(1)-I(1) bond lengths are 2.796 Å. In the second Pd site, Pd(2) is bonded to eight equivalent Pd(1) and four equivalent Al(1) atoms to form PdAl₄Pd₈ cuboctahedra that share corners with four equivalent Pd(2)Al₄Pd₈ cuboctahedra, faces with four equivalent Pd(2)Al₄Pd₈ cuboctahedra, and faces with four equivalent Al(1)Pd₁₂ cuboctahedra. All Pd(2)-Al(1) bond lengths are 2.873 Å. Al(1) is bonded to four equivalent Pd(2) and eight equivalent Pd(1) atoms to form AlPd₁₂ cuboctahedra that share corners with four equivalent Al(1)Pd₁₂ cuboctahedra, faces with four equivalent Pd(2)Al₄Pd₈ cuboctahedra, and faces with four equivalent Al(1)Pd₁₂ cuboctahedra. I(1) is bonded in a 4-coordinate geometry to four equivalent Pd(1) atoms.

TiS₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one TiS₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a 8-coordinate geometry to two equivalent S(1)+1.33-, two equivalent S(2)+1.33-, and four equivalent S(3)+1.33- atoms. Both Ti(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.499 Å. Both Ti(1)-S(2) bond lengths are 2.499 Å. There are two shorter (2.465 Å) and two longer (2.667 Å) Ti(1)-S(3) bond lengths. There are three inequivalent S+1.33- sites. In the first S+1.33- site, S(1)+1.33- is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the second S+1.33- site, S(2)+1.33- is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ atoms. In the third S+1.33- site, S(3)+1.33- is bonded to four equivalent Ti(1)⁴⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing STi₄ trigonal pyramids.

BiBr₃ is Bismuth triodide-like structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one BiBr₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Br(1,2,3)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing BiBr₆ octahedra. All Bi(1)-Br(1,2,3) bond lengths are 2.896 Å. Br(1,2,3)¹⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to two equivalent Bi(1)³⁺ atoms.

P₄Se₅ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic Pc space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two P₄Se₅ clusters. There are four inequivalent P+2.50+ sites. In the first P+2.50+ site, P(1)+2.50+ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Se(1)²⁻ atom. The P(1)-Se(1) bond length is 2.237 Å. In the second P+2.50+ site, P(2)+2.50+ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one Se(2)²⁻ and one Se(4)²⁻ atom. The P(2)-Se(2) bond length is 2.317 Å. The P(2)-Se(4) bond length is 2.324 Å. In the third P+2.50+ site, P(3)+2.50+ is bonded in a trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Se(3)²⁻, one Se(4)²⁻, and one Se(5)²⁻ atom. The P(3)-Se(3) bond length is 2.304 Å. The P(3)-Se(4) bond length is 2.303 Å. The P(3)-Se(5) bond length is 2.131 Å. In the fourth P+2.50+ site, P(4)+2.50+ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to one Se(1)²⁻, one Se(2)²⁻, and one Se(3)²⁻ atom. The P(4)-Se(1) bond length is 2.334 Å. The P(4)-Se(2) bond length is 2.289 Å. The P(4)-Se(3) bond length is 2.304 Å. There are five inequivalent Se²⁻ sites. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(1)+2.50+ and one P(4)+2.50+ atom. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(2)+2.50+ and one P(4)+2.50+ atom. In the third Se²⁻ site, Se(3)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to one P(3)+2.50+ and one P(4)+2.50+ atom. In the fourth Se²⁻ site, Se(4)²⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to one P(2)+2.50+ and one P(3)+2.50+ atom. In the fifth Se²⁻ site, Se(5)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one P(3)+2.50+ atom.

Re(AgCl₃)₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Re(AgCl₃)₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Re(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form ReCl₆ octahedra that share edges with six equivalent Ag(1)Cl₆ pentagonal pyramids. All Re(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.383 Å. Ag(1)¹⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form distorted AgCl₆ pentagonal pyramids that share edges with three equivalent Re(1)Cl₆ octahedra and edges with three equivalent Ag(1)Cl₆ pentagonal pyramids. There are three shorter (2.635 Å) and three longer (2.970 Å) Ag(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Re(1)⁴⁺ and two equivalent Ag(1)¹⁺ atoms.

Nb₃IrSe₈ is trigonal omega-derived structured and crystallizes in the triclinic P1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Nb₃IrSe₈ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are two inequivalent Nb⁴⁺ sites. In the first Nb⁴⁺ site, Nb(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Se(1,4)²⁻; two equivalent Se(2,5)²⁻; and two equivalent Se(3,6)²⁻ atoms to form NbSe₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Ir(1)Se₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Nb(2,3)Se₆ octahedra. Both Nb(1)-Se(1,4) bond lengths are 2.584 Å. Both Nb(1)-Se(2,5) bond lengths are 2.632 Å. There is one shorter (2.657 Å) and one longer (2.658 Å) Nb(1)-Se(3,6) bond length. In the second Nb⁴⁺ site, Nb(2,3)⁴⁺ is bonded to one Se(1,4)²⁻; one Se(3,6)²⁻; two equivalent Se(2,5)²⁻; and two equivalent Se(7,8)²⁻ atoms to form NbSe₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Nb(1)Se₆ octahedra; edges with two equivalent Nb(2,3)Se₆ octahedra; and edges with two equivalent Ir(1)Se₆ octahedra. The Nb(2,3)-Se(1,4) bond length is 2.568 Å. The Nb(2,3)-Se(3,6) bond length is 2.688 Å. There is one shorter (2.591 Å) and one longer (2.656 Å) Nb(2,3)-Se(2,5) bond length. There is one shorter (2.529 Å) and one longer (2.732 Å) Nb(2,3)-Se(7,8) bond length. Ir(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent Se(1,4)²⁻; two equivalent Se(3,6)²⁻; and two equivalent Se(7,8)²⁻ atoms to form IrSe₆ octahedra that share edges with two equivalent Nb(1)Se₆ octahedra and edges with four equivalent Nb(2,3)Se₆ octahedra. Both Ir(1)-Se(1,4) bond lengths are 2.562 Å. Both Ir(1)-Se(3,6) bond lengths are 2.561 Å. Both Ir(1)-Se(7,8) bond lengths are 2.559 Å. There are four inequivalent Se²⁻ sites. In the first Se²⁻ site, Se(1,4)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to one Nb(1)⁴⁺; one Nb(2,3)⁴⁺; and one Ir(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the second Se²⁻ site, Se(2,5)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Nb(1)⁴⁺ and two equivalent Nb(2,3)⁴⁺ atoms. In the third Se²⁻ site, Se(3,6)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Nb(1)⁴⁺; one Nb(2,3)⁴⁺; and one Ir(1)⁴⁺ atom. In the fourth Se²⁻ site, Se(7,8)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to two equivalent Nb(2,3)⁴⁺ and one Ir(1)⁴⁺ atom.

SbBr₃ is Indium-like structured and crystallizes in the orthorhombic Pmn2₁ space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of two SbBr₃ clusters. Sb(1)³⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Br(2)¹⁻ and two equivalent Br(1)¹⁻ atoms. The Sb(1)-Br(2) bond length is 2.570 Å. Both Sb(1)-Br(1) bond lengths are 2.598 Å. There are two inequivalent Br¹⁻ sites. In the first Br¹⁻ site, Br(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Sb(1)³⁺ atom. In the second Br¹⁻ site, Br(2)¹⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Sb(1)³⁺ atom.

MoO₃ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one MoO₃ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Mo(1)⁶⁺ is bonded in a 6-coordinate geometry to one O(1)²⁻, two equivalent O(3)²⁻, and three equivalent O(2)²⁻ atoms. The Mo(1)-O(1) bond length is 1.675 Å. There is one shorter (1.767 Å) and one longer (2.156 Å) Mo(1)-O(3) bond length. There are two shorter (1.946 Å) and one longer (2.441 Å) Mo(1)-O(2) bond length. There are three inequivalent O²⁻ sites. In the first O²⁻ site, O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one Mo(1)⁶⁺ atom. In the second O²⁻ site, O(2)²⁻ is bonded in a 2-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Mo(1)⁶⁺ atoms. In the third O²⁻ site, O(3)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted linear geometry to two equivalent Mo(1)⁶⁺ atoms.

SmS crystallizes in the tetragonal P4/nmm space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one SmS sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sm(1)²⁺ is bonded to five equivalent S(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing SmS₅ square pyramids. S(1)²⁻ is bonded to five equivalent Sm(1)²⁺ atoms to form a mixture of distorted edge and corner-sharing SSm₅ square pyramids.

PdSe₂ crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/c space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one PdSe₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Pd(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a square co-planar geometry to four equivalent Se(1)²⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (2.454 Å) and two longer (2.466 Å) Pd(1)-Se(1) bond lengths. Se(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted trigonal non-coplanar geometry to two equivalent Pd(1)⁴⁺ and one Se(1)²⁻ atom. The Se(1)-Se(1) bond length is 2.423 Å.

GeTe crystallizes in the trigonal P3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one GeTe sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ge(1)²⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms. All Ge(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.866 Å. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Ge(1)²⁺ atoms.

WO₂ is Cyanogen Chloride-derived structured and crystallizes in the hexagonal P6/mmm space group. The structure is zero-dimensional and consists of one WO₂ cluster. W(1)⁴⁺ is bonded in a linear geometry to two equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. Both W(1)-O(1) bond lengths are 1.798 Å. O(1)²⁻ is bonded in a single-bond geometry to one W(1)⁴⁺ atom.

Bi₁₄Te₁₃S₈ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Bi₁₄Te₁₃S₈ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. There are three inequivalent Bi³⁺ sites. In the first Bi³⁺ site, Bi(1)³⁺ is bonded to three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ and three equivalent S(2)²⁻ atoms to form BiTe₃S₃ octahedra that share corners with three equivalent Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra, edges with three equivalent Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra, and edges with six equivalent Bi(3)Te₂S₄ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 2°. All Bi(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 3.057 Å. All Bi(1)-S(2) bond lengths are 3.072 Å. In the second Bi³⁺ site, Bi(2)³⁺ is bonded to one Te(1)²⁻, one Te(3)²⁻, two equivalent Te(2)²⁻, and two equivalent S(2)²⁻ atoms to form BiTe₄S₂ octahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Bi(3)Te₂S₄ octahedra,  a cornercorner with one Bi(1)Te₃S₃ octahedra,  a cornercorner with one Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra,  an edgeedge with one Bi(1)Te₃S₃ octahedra, edges with four equivalent Bi(3)Te₂S₄ octahedra, and edges with four equivalent Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles range from 0-4°. The Bi(2)-Te(1) bond length is 3.053 Å. The Bi(2)-Te(3) bond length is 3.188 Å. There is one shorter (3.045 Å) and one longer (3.063 Å) Bi(2)-Te(2) bond length. There is one shorter (3.065 Å) and one longer (3.101 Å) Bi(2)-S(2) bond length. In the third Bi³⁺ site, Bi(3)³⁺ is bonded to one Te(1)²⁻, one Te(2)²⁻, one S(1)²⁻, and three equivalent S(2)²⁻ atoms to form BiTe₂S₄ octahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra, corners with two equivalent Bi(3)Te₂S₄ octahedra, edges with two equivalent Bi(1)Te₃S₃ octahedra, edges with three equivalent Bi(3)Te₂S₄ octahedra, and edges with four equivalent Bi(2)Te₄S₂ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles range from 1-4°. The Bi(3)-Te(1) bond length is 3.077 Å. The Bi(3)-Te(2) bond length is 3.081 Å. The Bi(3)-S(1) bond length is 2.760 Å. There are a spread of Bi(3)-S(2) bond distances ranging from 2.994-3.019 Å. There are three inequivalent Te²⁻ sites. In the first Te²⁻ site, Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Bi(1)³⁺, one Bi(2)³⁺, and one Bi(3)³⁺ atom. In the second Te²⁻ site, Te(2)²⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to one Bi(3)³⁺ and two equivalent Bi(2)³⁺ atoms. In the third Te²⁻ site, Te(3)²⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Bi(2)³⁺ atoms to form TeBi₆ octahedra that share edges with six equivalent S(2)Bi₆ octahedra. There are two inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Bi(3)³⁺ atoms. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded to one Bi(1)³⁺, two equivalent Bi(2)³⁺, and three equivalent Bi(3)³⁺ atoms to form SBi₆ octahedra that share  an edgeedge with one Te(3)Bi₆ octahedra and edges with five equivalent S(2)Bi₆ octahedra.

Ti₂PTe₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Ti₂PTe₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Ti(1)+3.50+ is bonded to three equivalent P(1)³⁻ and three equivalent Te(1)²⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing TiTe₃P₃ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Ti(1)-P(1) bond lengths are 2.489 Å. All Ti(1)-Te(1) bond lengths are 2.791 Å. P(1)³⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Ti(1)+3.50+ atoms to form edge-sharing PTi₆ octahedra. Te(1)²⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Ti(1)+3.50+ atoms.

CoCl₂ is trigonal omega-like structured and crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CoCl₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Co(1)²⁺ is bonded to six equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form edge-sharing CoCl₆ octahedra. All Co(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.422 Å. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent Co(1)²⁺ atoms.

Sc₂NCl₂ crystallizes in the trigonal P̅3m1 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one Sc₂NCl₂ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Sc(1)+2.50+ is bonded to three equivalent N(1)³⁻ and three equivalent Cl(1)¹⁻ atoms to form a mixture of edge and corner-sharing ScN₃Cl₃ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedra are not tilted. All Sc(1)-N(1) bond lengths are 2.273 Å. All Sc(1)-Cl(1) bond lengths are 2.567 Å. N(1)³⁻ is bonded to six equivalent Sc(1)+2.50+ atoms to form edge-sharing NSc₆ octahedra. Cl(1)¹⁻ is bonded in a 3-coordinate geometry to three equivalent Sc(1)+2.50+ atoms.

KTlO is trigonal omega-derived structured and crystallizes in the monoclinic P2₁/m space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one KTlO sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. K(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. There are two shorter (2.626 Å) and one longer (2.651 Å) K(1)-O(1) bond length. Tl(1)¹⁺ is bonded in a distorted T-shaped geometry to three equivalent O(1)²⁻ atoms. There is one shorter (2.367 Å) and two longer (2.515 Å) Tl(1)-O(1) bond lengths. O(1)²⁻ is bonded to three equivalent K(1)¹⁺ and three equivalent Tl(1)¹⁺ atoms to form edge-sharing OK₃Tl₃ octahedra.

CrP₂S₇ crystallizes in the monoclinic C2 space group. The structure is two-dimensional and consists of one CrP₂S₇ sheet oriented in the (0, 0, 1) direction. Cr(1)⁴⁺ is bonded to two equivalent S(1)²⁻, two equivalent S(2)²⁻, and two equivalent S(3)²⁻ atoms to form CrS₆ octahedra that share corners with two equivalent P(1)S₄ tetrahedra and edges with two equivalent P(1)S₄ tetrahedra. Both Cr(1)-S(1) bond lengths are 2.401 Å. Both Cr(1)-S(2) bond lengths are 2.385 Å. Both Cr(1)-S(3) bond lengths are 2.358 Å. P(1)⁵⁺ is bonded to one S(1)²⁻, one S(2)²⁻, one S(3)²⁻, and one S(4)²⁻ atom to form PS₄ tetrahedra that share  a cornercorner with one Cr(1)S₆ octahedra,  a cornercorner with one P(1)S₄ tetrahedra, and  an edgeedge with one Cr(1)S₆ octahedra. The corner-sharing octahedral tilt angles are 65°. The P(1)-S(1) bond length is 2.028 Å. The P(1)-S(2) bond length is 2.042 Å. The P(1)-S(3) bond length is 2.041 Å. The P(1)-S(4) bond length is 2.139 Å. There are four inequivalent S²⁻ sites. In the first S²⁻ site, S(1)²⁻ is bonded in a bent 120 degrees geometry to one Cr(1)⁴⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the second S²⁻ site, S(2)²⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to one Cr(1)⁴⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the third S²⁻ site, S(3)²⁻ is bonded in an L-shaped geometry to one Cr(1)⁴⁺ and one P(1)⁵⁺ atom. In the fourth S²⁻ site, S(4)²⁻ is bonded in a water-like geometry to two equivalent P(1)⁵⁺ atoms.
